    "contenu": "### Carignan\n**Pronunciation:** kah-ree-nyahn\n\nCarignan, sometimes spelled with an e as Carignane, is notable as the second most planted red wine grape globally after Grenache and ranks within the top ten of all wine grapes planted worldwide. This position would signify an achievement if its cultivation were always based on optimal use; however, this isn't always the case. It is famed for its volume over its distinction. Often found in France, primarily used as a blending grape, Carignan can be crafted into dry red or ros√© table wines, or even sweet and fortified dessert wines which are delicious, well-balanced and, in ideal conditions, suitable for aging. However, not all Carignan and Carignan-based wines achieve high recognition. Many quality Carignan wines exist, and further details can be found on www.closdugarvillas.com/carignanrenaissance.htm.\n\n#### Alternative Names:\n- Carignane (U.S.A),\n- Carignano (Italy),\n- Cari√±ena, Mazuelo (Spain)\n\n#### Styles:\n- Medium-full to full-bodied dry red wine,\n- Medium-bodied dry ros√©,\n- Full-bodied fortified dessert wine\n\n#### Sometimes Blended With:\n- Cabernet Franc, \n- Cabernet Sauvignon, \n- Cinsaut,\n- Grenache,\n- Syrah,\n- Merlot,\n- Mourv√®dre (France),\n- Grapes in the Cabernet family,\n- Garnacha, \n- Tempranillo (Spain)\n\n#### Flavor Lexicon:\n- **RED**\n  - **Fruit:** Blackberry, black olive, plum\n  - **Wood:** Baking spice, bitter chocolate, carob\n  - **Other:** Black pepper\n\n- **ROS√â**\n  - **Fruit:** Orange, rhubarb, sour cherry, strawberry, tangerine, watermelon\n\n- **SWEET**\n  - **Fruit:** Dried cherry, plum, prune, raisin\n  - **Wood:** Vanilla\n  - **Earth:** Gravel, mineral, stone\n  - **Other:** Fruitcake, leather, white pepper\n\n#### Similar Slips:\n- Zinfandel or Petite Sirah in a sharp and tart style, or lean and rustic versions of Pinot Noir or Barbera."
