    "source": "inconnu_3237",
    "contenu": "### Document Content Analysis\n\n#### Method 1: M√©thode de la cuve close\n- **Overview**: Invented in 1907 at the University of wine in Montpellier by Auguste Charmat. This method consists of adding sugar and yeast to wine after alcoholic fermentation to initiate a second fermentation within a sealed tank (cuve close). This is done to ensure carbon dioxide is dissolved into the wine.\n- **Production Area Requirement**: The method must be indicated on the label.\n\n#### Method 2: M√©thode Rurale ou Ancestrale\n- **Overview**: Characterized by the cooling of fermentation. If fermentation is not yet completed, the wine is bottled to finish fermenting.\n- **Characteristics**: The results are very irregular as the wine isn't limpid, and there is a significant risk of bottle explosion.\n- **Production Areas**: \n  - Ayse\n  - Clairette de Die (m√©thode dioise)\n  - Anjou\n  - Gaillac\n  - Blanquette de Limoux (m√©thode ancestrale)\n\n#### Method 3: M√©thode Champenoise ou traditionnelle\n- **Overview**: Similar to the first method, after alcoholic fermentation, sugar and yeast are added to the wine which is then bottled. These bottles are sealed tightly to allow the second fermentation to commence.\n- **Production Areas**: \n  - Champagne\n  - Cr√©mants\n  - Clairette de Die\n  - Gaillac mousseux\n  - Blanquette\n  - Arbois mousseux\n\nThis document outlines three key methods used in wine fermentation and their associated production regions which must adhere to specific labeling and production standards."
