    "contenu": "**Spanish Lamb Ragout with Roasted Sweet Peppers**\n\n*Recommended Wine:* For rich, oaky Cabernet Sauvignons with jammy fruit (New World-style)\n\n*Serves:* 6\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 4 whole red bell peppers\n- 3 pounds lamb shoulder, fat and sinew trimmed, cut into 2-inch cubes, or 6 small lamb shanks\n\n**Marinade:**\n- 1 tablespoon sweet paprika or piment√≥n de la Vera (Spanish smoked paprika)\n- 2 teaspoons ground cumin\n- 1 bay leaf, crumbled\n- ¬Ω cup dry red wine\n- ¬º cup extra virgin olive oil\n- ¬Ω cup mild olive oil, or more as needed\n- Salt and freshly ground black pepper\n- 2 yellow onions, chopped\n- 2 tablespoons finely minced garlic\n- 2 tablespoons sweet paprika or piment√≥n de la Vera\n- 2 teaspoons ground cumin \n- ¬Ω cup dry red wine\n- 1¬Ω cups meat stock\n- 5 tablespoons tomato paste\n- ¬º cup chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley\n- 1 cup oil-cured black olives\n\n**Instructions:**\n1. **Prepare Peppers:**\n   - Place the bell peppers under the broiler or over a direct flame on a grill or stovetop. \n   - Use tongs to turn the peppers a few times until they are charred almost black on all sides.\n   - Place in a plastic container or plastic bag and let stand for 30 minutes. Scrape away all the charred peel, discard the seeds and thick ribs, and cut the peppers into wide strips.\n   - Set aside. *Note: Can be prepared up to 4 days ahead of time. To store, toss the peppers with olive oil to coat and refrigerate.*\n\n2. **Marinate Lamb:**\n   - Place the lamb in a large nonaluminum container.\n   - In a medium bowl, combine 1 tablespoon sweet paprika, 2 teaspoons cumin, and the bay leaf. Whisk in ¬Ω cup wine and ¬º cup oil.\n   - Pour over the meat. Cover with plastic wrap and marinate overnight in the refrigerator.\n\n3. **Cooking:**\n   - Bring the marinated lamb to room temperature.\n   - Remove the lamb from the marinade and pat dry. Cook as desired (note that specific cooking instructions are not provided in the document)."
