    "source": "396118758-Understanding-Wines-Explaining-Style-and-Quality.pdf_page_89",
    "contenu": "The document provided is a page focusing on understanding the wine regions of Bordeaux in France, explaining the style and quality of wines from different appellations within the region. Here's a breakdown of the structured content from the text:\n\n### KEY MAP\n- The map displays the Bordeaux wine region, color-coded to indicate different sub-regions and appellations. Labels such as \"M√©doc\", \"Saint-Est√®phe\", \"Pauillac\", \"Haut-M√©doc\", and \"Saint-Julien\" and several others highlight specific areas within Bordeaux.\n\n### TITLE\n- Understanding Wines: Explaining Style and Quality\n\n### TEXT CONTENT\n\n#### Bordeaux Appellations Overview\n- Bordeaux's wine region is divided into multiple appellations which cover a vast area down to the smallest commune appellations. In Bordeaux, the numerous appellations don't form a neat hierarchy but vary in quality and it's easier to look at them in groups based on the styles of wine produced.\n\n#### Generic Appellations\n- The output of the generic appellations in Bordeaux is primarily red and labeled either as **Bordeaux** or **Bordeaux Sup√©rieur**. The latter has slightly stricter application rules and requires higher alcohol content in the final wine. Labels like Bordeaux Ros√© and Bordeaux Clairet exist, with standard Bordeaux wines being robust and Bordeaux Ros√© being fruity and increasingly darker. Bordeaux Clairet is popular in the French market, typified by a richer and fuller body.\n  \n#### The Reds of M√©doc and Graves\n- **M√©doc** to the north of Bordeaux city, known for Cabernet Sauvignon-led blends. Sandy soil in the lower M√©doc and clay, however in higher areas like Bas-M√©doc, there are outcrops of gravel which results in heavier wine styles moving from the north to the south.\n- **Haut-M√©doc** within a higher M√©doc area, consists of smaller appellations like Saint-Est√®phe, Pauillac, Saint-Julien, and Margaux, known for rich, full-bodied wines with blackcurrant fruit and higher tannin levels often described as grippy when young with potential for aging.\n- **Graves** and **Pessac-L√©ognan**, immediately south of Bordeaux city, are known for gravelly soils appropriate for long-aging dry white wines, dominated by varieties like Sauvignon Blanc exhibiting a vibrant grassy character.\n\nThis textual summary contextualizes the geographical and stylistic diversity within Bordeaux's wine appellations according to the provided document, highlighting key aspects that affect the style and quality of the wines produced in each region."
