    "source": "the-elements-of-taste.pdf_page_82",
    "contenu": "The document is a recipe that includes instructions for preparing \"Watercress Broth\" and \"Spring Onion Stew.\" It provides a number of servings, ingredients, and detailed cooking methods. Below are the structured components of the document:\n\n### SERVES 4\n\n### Watercress Broth\n- **Ingredients:**\n  - 2 bunches watercress\n  - 1 tablespoon butter\n  - 2 tablespoons finely diced spring onions (or scallions)\n  - 1 clove garlic, slivered\n  - 1/3 cup roughly chopped fresh ginger\n  - 2 cups chicken stock\n  - 1 cup water\n\n- **Instructions:**\n  1. Pluck 1¬º cups of watercress leaves and set aside for topping.\n  2. Melt the butter in a saucepan over medium-high heat.\n  3. Add the onions, garlic, and ginger and cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant.\n  4. Add the remaining watercress (stems and all) to the skillet.\n  5. Add stock and water, cover, and simmer about ¬Ω hour.\n  6. Strain the broth through a fine sieve and reserve 1 cup for the stew and the remaining liquid for the sauce.\n\n### Spring Onion Stew\n- **Ingredients:**\n  - 2 tablespoons butter\n  - 1 bunch spring onions (or three medium white onions), thinly sliced\n  - Kosher salt\n  - Freshly ground white pepper\n  - 1 cup watercress broth (from the above recipe)\n\n- **Instructions:**\n  1. Preheat the oven to 300 degrees Fahrenheit.\n  2. Melt 1 tablespoon butter in a large ovenproof skillet over medium-high heat.\n  3. Add the onions, season with salt and white pepper, and cook until the onions have softened.\n  4. Add the cup of watercress broth and bring to a simmer.\n  5. Cover the pot and braise in the oven until the onions are very tender, approximately 30-45 minutes.\n  6. Remove the skillet from the oven; add the remaining butter and brown, stirring constantly, over medium-high heat.\n  7. Set the onions aside in a warm place.\n\nThe recipe emphasizes the use of onions across both dishes, highlighting their importance in enhancing the flavors of the main ingredients such as watercress and in the overall dishes."
