    "contenu": "The document provided is a detailed exposition on the historical context and evolution of chocolate, focusing on its preparation, consumption, and cultural significance across various regions and time periods. Below is the structured content from the text:\n\n### Chocolate Preparation and Cultural Context\n1. **Initial Preparation**:\n    - **For the Maya and Aztecs**: Chocolate was made by picking out cacao kernels, drying them, roasting them in an earthen pan over a fire, grinding them with stones, and then slowly mixing them with water, sometimes adding a little spice. This preparation was considered an intoxicating drink.\n   \n2. **Early European Modification**:\n    - **Additions**: Early Europeans added flavors like aromatic flowers, vanilla, chili, wild honey, and achicote to the chocolate.\n    - **Consumption Style**: It was transformed from a spicy drink to one including cinnamon, cloves, anise, almonds, hazelnuts, vanilla, orange-flower water, and musk. \n    - **Serving Methods**: Prepared by drying, grinding cacao beans, then heating with spices to melt the paste into solid blocks or drinking it hot or cold.\n\n### Early Commercial and Industrial Evolution\n1. **Factories**: The first chocolate factories started around 1580 in Spain, spreading to Italy, France, and England within 70 years.\n2. **Reduction in Flavorings**: These countries gradually removed many of the added flavorings.\n\n### Innovations and Consumption in Europe\n1. **17th Century London**: Chocolate houses, similar to today's specialty coffeehouses, thrived; chocolate was often served as hot drink mixed with milk.\n2. **European Confections**:\n   - **18th Century**: Included recipes like marzipans, biscuits, ices, mousses, and notable dishes like lasagna and polenta with chocolate.\n   - **French Encyclop√©die**: Described as chocolate with half-sugar and vanilla.\n   - **Instant Meal Concept**: Seen as an emergency meal due to its ease of preparation and satisfying nature.\n\n### Quick Consumption\n- **Practical Usage**: Chocolate could be eaten as a tablet or mixed with hot water when in a hurry to leave lodgings or for a quick meal, symbolizing a sort of early \"instant breakfast\".\n\n### Late 19th Century\n- **Reference in Literature**: Mentioned in Gunter‚Äôs Modern Encyclopedia indicating its embedded cultural and culinary status.\n\nThe document echoes the rich cultural heritage of chocolate and its transformation from a luxury spice-laden drink in Mesoamerica to a staple everyday item in Europe, illustrating how it adapted over time in ingredient usage and consumption practices."
