    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_711",
    "contenu": "The document provided is an informative excerpt about the cacao bean and related topics, including its varieties, storage, fermentation and drying processes. Here is a structured summary of the content:\n\n## The Cacao Bean\n- **Name and Origin**: The cacao tree, known scientifically as *Theobroma cacao*, is described as the \"food of the gods\". It is an evergreen that grows between 20¬∞ north and south of the equator and reaches about 20 feet in height. It produces fibrous pods containing seeds embedded in sweet-tart pulp.\n  \n- **Varieties**: \n  - **Criollo**: Mild flavors, resembling flowers and tea, disease-prone, low-yielding.\n  - **Forastero**: High-yielding, robust, provide the majority of the world‚Äôs cacao crop. Known for less delicate flavors.\n  - **Trinitario**: Hybrids of Criollo and Forastero; mixed qualities.\n\n- **Global Production**: \n  - West Africa (Ivory Coast and Ghana) accounts for over half of the world's cacao production.\n  - Indonesia and Brazil are also significant producers.\n\n## Storage and Defensive Cells\n- **Composition**: Cacao beans primarily consist of the embryo‚Äôs storage leaves, or cotyledons, making up about 80% of the cells. These cotyledons store protein and fats (including cocoa butter) used in germination.\n- **Defensive Role**: Around 20% of the cells are defensive, deterring animals and microbes from the seeds. These contain phenolic compounds and alkaloids, which are bitter and water-intensive.\n  \n## Fermentation and Drying\n- **Process Overview**: Fermentation of cacao is crucial for developing chocolate's flavor but varies significantly in quality depending on the method and environment. It could range from expertly managed to neglected, resulting in under or over-fermented beans.\n\n  The document also includes illustrative visuals of the cacao pods and beans alongside microscopic views of the beans' internal structure, highlighting the defensive cells rich in alkaloids and phenolic compounds. \n\nOverall, the text provides a thorough insight into the biological and agricultural aspects of cacao production, emphasizing the complexity inherent in producing the raw materials for chocolate."
