    "source": "the-wine-bible-karen-macneil.pdf_page_808",
    "contenu": "The document discusses the history and characteristics of the Rioja wine region in Spain.\n\n### Main Points:\n1. **Geography and Reputation**:\n   - Rioja spans 75 miles (120 kilometers) along the Ebro River in northern Spain, covering 157,000 acres (63,500 hectares).\n   - It is renowned for its red wines made primarily from tempranillo grapes.\n   - The region is often compared to Bordeaux in France, due to similar wine characteristics and historical ties.\n\n2. **Historical Influence**:\n   - Rioja's reputation began with the Camino Franc√©s in the Middle Ages, a pilgrimage route through the region.\n   - The practice of aging wine in oak barrels, inspired by the French, began in 1780 with Manuel Quintano, who adopted the Bordeaux method.\n\n3. **Evolution of Winemaking Practices**:\n   - Initially using large French oak casks, later the use of small barrels became prevalent.\n   - The adoption of small barrels happened when Spaniards realized their benefits for aging wines and started importing North American oak to make their own barrels.\n\n4. **Etymology**:\n   - The name \"Rioja\" is likely derived from the Rio Oja, one of the tributaries of the Ebro River.\n   - The region became a key stopping point for pilgrims trekking the Camino Franc√©s due to the presence of Santa Domingo de la Calzada‚Äôs monastery, enhancing its early prominence.\n\n5. **Late 19th century development**:\n   - Rioja and Pened√©s benefited from the phylloxera outbreak in French vineyards.\n   - French wine merchants (comisionados) helped expand the vineyard area in Rioja by 40,000 acres (16,200 hectares) in response to demand.\n\n6. **Contribution of French Winemakers**:\n   - Some French tradesmen who initially came to buy wine stayed and established their own vineyards (bodegas).\n   - They innovated by purchasing grapes from local growers and aging the wine in small oak barrels, thereby establishing a new tradition in winemaking in Rioja.\n\nThis summary highlights Rioja's rich heritage influenced by geographical, cultural, and economic factors, making it a prestigious and historical wine region influenced significantly by French practices and even tragedy in French vineyards."
