    "source": "and_the_wines_for_wine",
    "contenu": "The document provides insights and suggestions on selecting wines for group dining, focusing on versatility and suitability for various tastes and food pairings. Here‚Äôs a structured outline of the document's main content:\n\n---\n\n**Title: Wine in Restaurants**\n\n### Guidelines for Choosing Wine\n\n- **Versatility is Key**\n  - When dining in groups, sommeliers prioritize wine versatility.\n  - Insider tips are offered for selecting wines during business dinners or family gatherings.\n\n### Specific Tips for Wine Selection\n\n1. **Favor Wines on the Lighter, Brighter End of the Style Spectrum That Deliver Flavor Without Weight**\n   - **Rationale:**\n     - Lighter wines are more versatile than heavier ones.\n     - They cleanse the palate and enhance food flavors without overpowering.\n   - **Examples of Suitable Light Wines:**\n     - Lemony veal Milanese, chicken quesadillas, or grilled salmon pair well with lighter wines.\n     - Recommended wines include sparkling wines, dry ros√©s, Sauvignon Blancs, Pinot Noirs, Rieslings, Gr√ºner Veltliners, and wines from northern France and northern and southern Spain.\n\n2. **With More Than Four People, Order Two Wines: One Red and One White**\n   - **Rationale:**\n     - The average person consumes about two glasses at dinner, and each bottle typically serves five glasses.\n   - **Benefit:**\n     - This ensures guests have the option to select from both types of wine and switch between them throughout different courses.\n\n### Practical Application\n- The document details practical strategies for enhancing the dining experience through adept wine selection, emphasizing suitability across a variety of dishes and personal preferences.\n\n--- \n\nThis synopsis pulls together the key points and recommendations from the document on how to choose wines effectively in a restaurant setting."
