    "source": "honey_nectar_bees_process_into",
    "contenu": "The provided document is a content-rich text focused on the topic of sugars and syrups, detailing the process of transforming nectar into honey and mentioning the use of honey ants as a sweeter. Here is the structured content extracted and categorized from the document:\n\n### Transforming Nectar into Honey\n1. **Process Overview**:\n   - Bees concentrate nectar by repeatedly pumping it in and out of themselves and evaporating the water content until it reduces to about 50 or 40%.\n   - They deposit the concentrated nectar on the honeycomb, built from the secretions of wax glands of worker bees.\n   - The continuous fanning by the bees and the structure of the honeycomb facilitate further moisture reduction until the water content drops below 20%.\n   - This process, known as \"ripening,\" takes about three weeks.\n\n2. **Honeycomb Structure**:\n   - Consists of a waxy network of hexagonal cylinders about 0.20 inch/5 mm across.\n\n3. **Final Steps**:\n   - Once sufficiently ripened, the honey is capped with wax to fill the honeycomb cells completely.\n\n### Honey Ripening\n1. **Enzymatic Action**:\n   - Involves bee enzymes converting sucrose to glucose and fructose, which are more water-soluble.\n   - Additional enzyme activities convert some glucose to gluconic acid and peroxides, decreasing honey‚Äôs pH to about 3.9.\n   - These changes make honey less hospitable to microbes and also provide antiseptic qualities.\n\n2. **Composition**:\n   - Ripening process changes the various components of raw honey by reacting with each other, leading to changes in color and flavor.\n   - Over 20 different sugars and substances are identified in ripened honey.\n\n### Anatomy of the Worker Bee\n- **Honey Storage**: Worker bees carry nectar in the honey sac, mixed with enzymes from various glands.\n- **Continual Processing**: The enzymes continue to act on the nectar until the bees return to the hive.\n\n### Sweet Ants\n- **Types and Geography**:\n   - Species include Melophorus, Camponotus, and Myrmecocystus found in Australia, Mexico, and the American southwest.\n- **Usage**:\n   - Honey ants store nectar in their swollen abdomens and are consumed by pinching off the abdomens and eating the honeydew either directly or by folding into tortillas.\n\nThe document combines detailed scientific processes with intriguing natural phenomena, providing an educational insight into the natural production and gathering of sugars."
