    "contenu": "The document is a page from a glossary section, specifically page 320, providing definitions of terms related to wine. Here's the structured extraction of the content:\n\n### GLOSSARY\n\n- **Acid adjustment**\n  - **Definition:** Manually adding acidity to a wine to increase its sharpness and balance. Usually added in the form of tartaric acid, which, when well done, is effective, but poorly executed adjustments can result in wines tasting painfully sharp and noticeably disjointed on the finish.\n\n- **Acidity**\n  - **Definition:** The level of acid in the wine. The perception of tartness or sharpness is critical to the wine‚Äôs structure and balance and to its compatibility with food. High acidity can contrast sharply with fat, rich, salty, greasy, or mildly spicy foods. It can also enhance the taste of quality ingredients, acting as a vinous highlighter.\n\n- **AOC (Appellation d'origine contr√¥l√©e)**\n  - **Definition:** Refers to geographic indications for wines and other agricultural products in countries where certification is managed by the Institut National des Appellations d‚ÄôOrigine (INAO). AOCs set specific yields, recognized grapes, and viticultural standards.\n\n- **Appellation**\n  - **Definition:** The geographic area from which a wine comes, usually identified on the wine label. In locales like Napa Valley or Champagne, the use of appellation names in labeling is legally restricted, and a wine using the name must contain a certain minimum percentage of local resources.\n\n- **Astringency**\n  - **Definition:** The puckery sensation in the mouth, often associated with tannins in red wines. It refers to a flavor sensation that is bitter but lacks the drying effect of tannins.\n\n- **Austerity**\n  - **Definition:** Often used to describe wines that are lean and sharp in nature, serving well as a contrast to rich dishes due to their unappealing nature alone.\n\n- **AVA (American viticultural area)**\n  - **Definition:** The American equivalent of a French AOC or Italian DOC. Unlike its European counterparts, AVAs only specify physical boundaries and do not mandate any specific winemaking or viticultural practices.\n\n- **Balance**\n  - **Definition:** A quality all winemakers strive for in wine, ensuring that acidity, tannin, oak, alcohol, and sweetness are present in appropriate proportions, aiming to prevent any single characteristic from dominating the rest. Balance is crucial not only in wine itself but also in pairing with food."
  },
